How Speech Becomes Text: An Interactive Visualization

Watch how your spoken words transform into written text, step by step.

The Big Picture

Converting speech to text is like translating between two completely different languages. Sound waves are continuous and flowing, while text is discrete symbols. This model learns to bridge that gap.

Input: The Audio Sample

Reference Text: "MISTER QUILTER IS THE APOSTLE OF THE MIDDLE CLASSES AND WE ARE GLAD TO WELCOME HIS GOSPEL"

This is what the speaker actually said. Our goal is to recover this text from the raw audio signal alone.

Step 1: Sound Waves

Speech starts as vibrations in the air. A microphone captures these vibrations 16,000 times per second, turning sound into numbers.

The ups and downs show how loud the sound is at each moment. Bigger waves = louder sounds.

Step 2: Frequency Analysis (Spectrogram)

Like a musical score shows different notes over time, a spectrogram shows different frequencies in the speech. Think of it as converting sound into a heat map.

Time flows left to right. Bottom = low sounds (like bass), Top = high sounds (like whistles). Bright = loud, Dark = quiet. The purple area on the right is just padding - ignore it.

What we're seeing:

  • Bottom rows: Deep voice tones
  • Middle rows: Vowel sounds (a, e, i, o, u)
  • Top rows: Consonants like 's' and 'f'

Step 3: Understanding Speech Sounds (Encoder)

The AI "listens" to the spectrogram and identifies speech patterns. It recognizes things like individual sounds, speaking pace, and voice characteristics.

This is what the AI "understands" about the audio. Each column is a moment in time. Brighter colors mean the AI detected something important at that moment.

What it's detecting:

  • Individual speech sounds (like "t", "s", "ah")
  • Whether sounds are voiced or whispered
  • Pitch and rhythm patterns
  • Speaker characteristics (accent, gender, age)

Important: At this stage, "to," "too," and "two" all look the same because they sound the same! The AI knows the sound but not yet the spelling.

Step 4: Translating to Text (Projector)

The projector's job: convert "what was heard" into "how to write it." This is where sound becomes text-ready.

Now the AI is thinking in text, not sound. It's figuring out spelling, punctuation, and capitalization.

The key trick:

The projector solves problems that sound alone can't answer:

  • "to" vs "too" vs "two" - Same sound, different spelling based on meaning
  • "their" vs "there" vs "they're" - Context determines which one
  • Question marks - Rising tone at the end add "?"
  • Capitalization - "apple" (fruit) vs "Apple" (company)

This isn't the final transcription! But it proves the projector is workingthe AI is now thinking in text-like patterns. The language model will clean this up into proper sentences.

How The Projector Works: Smart Gating

The projector uses a clever trick called SwiGLU - think of it like a smart gate that decides what information passes through.

Simple Analogy:

Imagine you're hearing the "s" sound. The projector asks: "Is there voice vibration?"

  • No vibration write "s" (like in "snake")
  • Yes vibration write "z" (like in "buzz")

It makes conditional decisions based on context, not just blind copying.

In The Visualization:

  • Top Left: The flowchart shows how information splits into two paths and combines intelligently
  • Bottom Left: Blue bars act as gates controlling orange bars, producing green output

The key insight: Simple math can't decide "to" vs "too" vs "two" - you need context-aware gating.

The Big Picture

You've just watched speech recognition happen in slow motion:

  1. Sound waves captured as numbers
  2. Spectrogram frequencies over time
  3. Encoder understands "what was said"
  4. Projector translates to "how to write it"

The magic? We only had to train the tiny projector (step 4). The encoder and language model were already trained on massive datasets. This makes building powerful speech recognition affordable for everyone.
